2025-06-14T18:22:36.084517Z assistant

Absolutely yes, I can help you determine the country of manufacture from your VIN (Vehicle Identification Number). The first character of your VIN indicates the country where the vehicle was assembled, and that's exactly what we need to figure out whether your vehicle was made in Japan, Mexico, or elsewhere.

Here's how it works:

First VIN Character Country
J Japan
3 Mexico
1 / 4 / 5 United States
K South Korea
S United Kingdom
... (many more)

So if you provide the full VIN (or just the first 3 characters, known as the WMI World Manufacturer Identifier), I can:

  1. Tell you the country of assembly.
  2. Help double-check parts compatibility (especially brake rotors/pads).
  3. Optionally, decode the full VIN to provide make, model, year, engine type, and factory-specific options this helps match OEM vs aftermarket fitment precisely.

Next Step:

Drop your VIN here, and Ill get you a clear answer no guesswork. Lets make sure you dont waste money on parts that dont fit.

2025-06-14T19:15:06.582311Z assistant

OK. If the caliper is off and the rotor still wont spin were looking at a deeper issue than pads or rotor fitment. That rotor should freely spin by hand when:

  • The wheel is off
  • The caliper is removed
  • The rotor is just sitting on the hub

If it doesnt, then yeah were in critical diagnosis mode.

Likely Causes (Ranked from Most to Least Common)

1. Emergency Brake (Drum-in-Hat style) is Engaged or Frozen

Even though you said no parking brake double check:

  • Rear rotors often have drum-style e-brake shoes inside
  • If the e-brake cable is seized, rusted, or stuck even slightly, the inner shoes can drag or lock the rotor solid

Test:
Tap the back of the rotor with a rubber mallet while trying to turn it. If it budges after a few taps seized e-brake is very likely.

2. Hub/Rotor Corrosion Rust-Welded

  • Rust can fuse the rotor to the hub
  • It feels locked, but its just rust bond the rotor face is stuck to the hub

Test:

  • With the wheel off and caliper removed, hit the edge of the rotor hat firmly with a hammer (rotational taps not straight on)
  • If the rotor pops loose or wiggles, that was your problem

3. Axle Nut / CV Joint Binding (Unlikely Unless Damaged)

  • If the front axle nut was overtightened or somethings wrong with the CV joint, it could seize rotation
  • Uncommon unless recent suspension or hub work was done

4. Wheel Bearing Collapse

  • If your wheel bearing failed catastrophically, it could seize up
  • Youd likely have heard whining or grinding beforehand

Test:
Try rocking the rotor side to side if theres play but no spin, it might be internal bearing failure.

Here's What to Try Right Now:

  1. Confirm caliper is 100% off (not just pivoted)
  2. Grab a hammer (or tire iron) and tap rotor in a circular motion around the center try loosening rust if thats it
  3. Try prying the rotor outward from behind using a flathead if its stuck

If after all that it still wont spin, send me:

  • A photo of the stuck rotor assembly with caliper off
  • Or just describe what you feel (play, no movement, slight grind, etc.)

Well get this fixed but now were looking at rust seizure or e-brake/hub failure. Still recoverable without new parts unless it's the bearing.

Thanks - also this video Im watching speaks of cleaning the hub extremely well before installing the new rotor because it can cause vibration and such issues within the next 4-5 k miles - think that could help me?

2025-06-14T22:20:40.950678Z assistant

Absolutely 1000% yes.

Cleaning the hub thoroughly is one of the most critical steps in doing brakes right, and its overlooked constantly especially by DIYers or rushed mechanics. If the hub surface isn't flat and rust-free, heres what can happen:

What Happens When the Hub Isn't Clean:

Problem Why It Happens
Rotor wobble / pulsation Rust or debris creates uneven contact rotor isn't perfectly flat against hub
Brake noise Uneven torque or contact points cause vibration or squealing under pressure
Rotor warping over time Heat builds unevenly due to poor mounting, leading to premature failure (35K miles as you said)
Drag or resistance If its bad enough, the rotor can sit crooked, making pad contact uneven

How to Do It Right:

  1. Remove old rotor

    • Might take mallet taps or some PB Blaster if rusted on

  2. Clean hub face with:

    • Wire brush or wheel drill attachment
    • Sandpaper/emery cloth (medium grit)
    • Brake cleaner to finish

  3. Check it with feel

    • Run your fingers across the hub it should feel smooth and flat, with no lip or scale buildup

  4. (Optional but pro move)

    • Use a tiny dab of anti-seize between the rotor and hub to prevent rust bonding in the future
      (Just a thin film dont get any on the braking surface)

Yes, It Could Be Exactly What Fixes It

If your rotor wouldnt spin freely or felt tight even with the caliper off, there's a strong chance the rotor is not seated flat. Rust buildup could be acting like a false shim.

Youre on the right track now. Clean the hell out of that hub and you'll feel the difference not just immediately but in the next 10,000 miles.

Let me know how it goes. Ive got you.

2025-06-14T22:38:11.703350Z assistant

If nothing spins even with the caliper fully removed and the rotor just sitting on the hub then were past a dirty hub. That means something deeper is locked up in the drivetrain or braking system.

Lets run through what that definitely means and what it might mean, step by step:

If the Rotor Does Not Spin with Caliper Removed:

1. Is the Car in Gear or Park?

  • If its a manual: Put it in neutral being in gear locks the drive axle
  • If its an automatic: Ensure its in neutral, not park
    Park will stop the wheels from turning, especially on front-wheel drive

Test:
Jack up both front wheels
Put it in neutral
Try spinning the rotor again

2. Check for Seized Wheel Bearing

  • With the rotor off or loose, try wiggling the hub side to side
  • If it rocks or grinds but wont turn, your wheel bearing may have seized

Clues:

  • Loud whining/grinding before this happened?
  • Brake heat or smoke previously?

3. Check CV Axle / Trans Binding

  • If the CV joint or transmission output shaft has jammed, it can lock the hub
  • This is rare unless the car was towed improperly, had a failed axle, or suffered major suspension damage

4. Rotor Rust-Welded to Drum Brake Inside (Rear-Style Only)

Doesnt apply to your front rotors, but if this was happening in the rear, the inner parking brake shoe could seize and lock the whole rotor from moving.

What You Can Try Right Now:

  1. Put the car in neutral
  2. Both front wheels off the ground
  3. Spin rotor or hub by hand
    • If it moves freely it was the transmission holding it still
    • If its still stuck, and the caliper is off:
      • Gently tap around the rotor with a rubber mallet
      • Try rotating the center hub (lug bolt or spindle) itself
      • If that doesn't move: likely bearing or CV/axle issue

If It's Totally Locked Even in Neutral:

Send me a close-up photo of:

  • The hub/rotor area
  • Behind the rotor (if you can see it)
  • And tell me which side youre working on (driver/passenger)

Well find the root. Youre closer to solving it than you might think it just depends on whats stuck and where.

Here's What to Do Next:

  1. Chock the rear wheels tight

    • Use bricks, wood, anything solid both sides if possible
    • You dont want any roll while you're under the car

  2. Put the car in Neutral

    • If automatic, just turn the key to accessory and shift
    • If manual, neutral is easy same safety applies

  3. Now try spinning the rotor (with caliper off)

    • It should now move freely if there's no mechanical bind

  • You're in the clear!
  • That means your hub and bearing are fine
  • Next step: deep clean the hub face, reseat the rotor, and rebuild from there

We pivot but at least weve ruled out Park as the cause.
